******
[2]
Date: Tue 29 Dec 2015
Source: Secretariat of Health Surveillance, Brazil Ministry of Health [in Portuguese, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
http://portalsaude.saude.gov.br/index.php/cidadao/principal/agencia-saude/21464-esclarecimento-sobre-caso-suspeito-no-rn


The Ministry of Health was notified by the Rio Grande do Norte Secretariat of Health of a suspected case of yellow fever [YF] in the capital, Natal, near the Dunas Park. A brief accompanied the investigation and offered help to the state and municipality health secretariats in conducting [investigation] of the case.

The Ministry classifies the case as suspected until the investigations are concluded, but reiterates that there is no epidemiological evidence to suggest that there is YF transmission in the municipality, in view that in the last 6 months, have been no recorded cases.

Concerning this case under investigation, the patient's symptoms began (which were not compatible with those of YF) on 28 Jun 2015. It is worth repeating that the patient had no history of travel to a YF-endemic area. The results of the laboratory tests done by the Instituto Evandro Chagas (IEC), in Belem in Para, and confirmed by the Instituto Adolfo Lutz (IAL) in Sao Paulo, suggested infection by the YF virus. The Ministry of Health was informed of the results on 22 Dec [2015]. However, it is still necessary to investigate further.

It is important to emphasize that there has been, up to now, no other suspected cases in humans or in non-human primates confirmed in RN state, so that no evidence exists of transmission of the virus to humans in the Natal municipality since 1930.

In order to clarify the case, other measures are underway: epidemiological investigation (collection of insects and other biological materials from primates in order to search for virus); conduct of additional laboratory tests on samples that have already been collected.

YF is an acute infectious febrile disease transmitted by mosquitoes. In the American Continent, there are urban and sylvan transmission cycles. The urban cycle has people as the principal host, with _Aedes aegypti_ as the main vector. In the sylvan transmission cycle, monkeys are the principal host and the vectors are sylvan mosquito species of the genus _Haemagogus_ and _Sabethes_. The last cases of urban transmission in Brazil occurred in 1942 in Acre. Since then, all the registered cases have been of the sylvan transmission cycle. The Ministry of Health offers YF vaccinations free of charge in its One Health System. The vaccine is recommended within the routine of the National Calendar of the National Program of Immunizations to people living in areas recommended for [YF] vaccination and travelers who go to those areas.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed-port@promedmail.org>

[The time between the death and the notification of the Ministry of Health is worrisome. - Mod.RNA

The key question is whether this patient died of an infection by YF virus or of some other pathogen. Mod.RNA raises some important questions in the above reports. ProMED awaits further information about the additional testing as it becomes available, and if YF virus infection is confirmed, further information about the circumstances under which the infection was acquired. As long as there are abundant populations of _Aedes aegypti_, there is always the risk that a viremic individual can come into that locality and initiate ongoing YF virus transmission. However, the above report appears to exclude that possibility in the Natal case. - Mod.TY

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3902261,811.]
